sections.example:
Let's say we want to display a welcome message if a user is logged in. We can create a simple React component for this. First, we define a state variable 'isLoggedIn' to track the user's login status. Then, in the render method, we can use a ternary operator to conditionally render the message. Here's how it looks: 

const WelcomeMessage = () => { 
  const isLoggedIn = true; // This would typically come from your app's state
  return ( 
    <div> 
      {isLoggedIn ? <h1>Welcome back!</h1> : <h1>Please log in.</h1>} 
    </div> 
  ); 
}; 

In this example, if 'isLoggedIn' is true, the component will render 'Welcome back!'. If false, it will show 'Please log in.' This demonstrates how you can control what the user sees based on their login status.
